  "prompt": "If cancer sometimes becomes resistant to treatment like chemotherapy, what about immunotherapy? Are the mechanisms different?",
  "response": "Immunotherapy and chemotherapy have different mechanisms of action, which can lead to different patterns of resistance. Here's a breakdown:\n\nChemotherapy Resistance Mechanisms:\n1. Genetic mutations in cancer cells\n2. Increased drug efflux\n3. DNA repair mechanisms\n4. Reduced drug uptake\n5. Altered cell metabolism\n\nImmunotherapy Resistance Mechanisms:\n1. Tumor microenvironment suppression of immune response\n2. Loss of antigen presentation\n3. Mutations that reduce immune recognition\n4. Downregulation of immune checkpoint proteins\n5. Immune cell exhaustion\n6. Emerging tumor subclones that evade immune surveillance\n\nKey Differences:\n- Chemotherapy directly attacks cancer cells\n- Immunotherapy stimulates the immune system to fight cancer\n\nWhile both treatments can develop resistance, immunotherapy's mechanisms are often more complex and adaptive. Researchers are developing combination strategies and next-generation immunotherapies to overcome resistance.\n\nEmerging approaches include:\n- Multi-targeted immunotherapies\n- Personalized vaccine strategies\n- Combination treatments\n- Targeting resistance pathways\n\nResearch is ongoing to better understand and counteract resistance in both treatment modalities.",
